# AI Supply Chain Control Tower

[![CI](https://github.com/hferrándiz/retail-demand-intelligence/actions/workflows/ci.yml/badge.svg)](https://github.com/hferrándiz/retail-demand-intelligence/actions/workflows/ci.yml)
[![License: MIT](https://img.shields.io/badge/License-MIT-yellow.svg)](https://opensource.org/licenses/MIT)
[![Python 3.11+](https://img.shields.io/badge/python-3.11+-blue.svg)](https://www.python.org/downloads/)

[Live Demo](https://huggingface.co/spaces/hferr%C3%A1ndiz/ai-supply-chain-control-tower) · [Documentation](docs/) · [Business Case](docs/01_business_case.md) · MIT License

> **Portfolio project** — Principal/Staff-grade system demonstrating end-to-end demand forecasting, inventory optimization, and operational analytics on real Walmart M5 data.

---

## What is this?

An end-to-end demand forecasting and inventory optimization platform built on the real Walmart M5 dataset (42,840 hierarchical series, 58.3M observations across 10 stores, 3,049 items, 1,969 days). The system ingests raw sales data, classifies demand patterns, engineers features without leakage, trains a global LightGBM model with calibrated prediction intervals, reconciles forecasts across a 12-level hierarchy, runs Monte Carlo inventory simulations, and delivers executive-grade analytics through a 7-page React dashboard — all deployed as a static site on Hugging Face Spaces.

**Why it exists:** most forecasting portfolios stop at "train a model and plot predictions." This system demonstrates the full operational stack: from data contracts and SCD Type 2 dimensions to newsvendor theory, from conformal calibration to CUSUM decay detection. The inventory layer is synthetic (explicitly documented) — the demand signal is real Walmart data.

---

## Architecture

Six layers from raw data to deployed dashboard:

```mermaid
graph TD
    subgraph RAW["RAW / Landing"]
        R1[M5 CSVs from Kaggle]
        R2[Open-Meteo JSON responses]
        R3[FRED API JSON responses]
    end

    subgraph BRONZE["BRONZE Layer"]
        B1[bronze_sales.parquet]
        B2[bronze_calendar.parquet]
        B3[bronze_prices.parquet]
        B4[bronze_weather.parquet]
        B5[bronze_macro.parquet]
    end

    subgraph SILVER["SILVER Layer"]
        S1[silver_sales_long.parquet<br/>partitioned by state/year]
        S2[silver_prices_daily.parquet<br/>forward-filled]
        S3[silver_calendar_enriched.parquet]
        S4[silver_weather_daily.parquet]
        S5[silver_macro_daily.parquet<br/>forward-filled with pub lag]
        S6[silver_demand_classification.parquet<br/>ADI/CV2 + ABC/XYZ]
    end

    subgraph WAREHOUSE["GOLD / Warehouse"]
        W1[fact_sales_daily]
        W2[fact_price_daily]
        W3[dim_product<br/>SCD Type 2]
        W4[dim_store]
        W5[dim_date]
        W6[dim_event]
        W7[mart_demand]
        W8[mart_executive]
    end

    subgraph ML["ML Engine"]
        F1[Feature Store<br/>v1.parquet]
        M1[Baselines<br/>SN/MA/Croston/TSB]
        M2[LightGBM Global<br/>point + quantile]
        M3[Conformal<br/>Calibration]
        M4[Reconciliation<br/>BU/TD/MinT/ERM]
    end

    subgraph INV["Inventory Engine"]
        I1[Synthetic Generator<br/>stock/orders/lead times]
        I2[Safety Stock + ROP]
        I3[Monte Carlo Simulator<br/>1000 paths x 90 days]
        I4[Policy Comparator<br/>sQ/sS/RS]
        I5[Scenario Engine<br/>5 what-ifs]
    end

    subgraph SERVE["Serving"]
        SV5[JSON assets<br/>< 5MB compressed]
    end

    subgraph FRONT["Frontend"]
        FE1[React + TS + Tailwind<br/>HF Static Space]
    end

    R1 --> B1 & B2 & B3
    R2 --> B4
    R3 --> B5
    B1 & B2 --> S1
    B3 --> S2
    B2 --> S3
    B4 --> S4
    B5 --> S5
    S1 --> S6
    S1 & S2 & S3 --> W1 & W2
    S6 --> W3
    W1 & W3 & W4 & W5 --> W7 & W8
    S1 & S2 & S3 & S4 & S5 & S6 --> F1
    F1 --> M1 & M2
    M2 --> M3
    M1 & M3 --> M4
    M4 --> SV5
    I5 --> SV5
    SV5 --> FE1
```

---

## Key Features

| Feature | Details |
|---------|---------|
| **Demand Classification** | ADI/CV² matrix classifies all 30,490 SKU-store series into Smooth/Erratic/Intermittent/Lumpy before any modeling |
| **LightGBM Global Model** | Single model across all series with 8 feature families (lags, rolling stats, calendar, price, intermittency, weather, macro, interactions) |
| **Calibrated Intervals** | Conformal prediction post-hoc calibration ensures ≥80% empirical coverage on [p10, p90] bands |
| **Hierarchical Reconciliation** | 12-level M5 hierarchy (42,840 series), MinT-Shrink method, 4 mandatory coherence checks |
| **Monte Carlo Simulation** | 1,000 paths × 90 days per SKU-store, 5.8 ms/series (NumPy vectorized) |
| **5 What-If Scenarios** | Demand surge, lead time delay, cost increase, high service level, combined stress |
| **SCD Type 2** | dim_product tracks classification history as ABC/XYZ/demand_class evolve over time |
| **Monitoring** | KS drift detection, PSI feature drift, CUSUM MAE decay, 6 alert rules, health report JSON |
| **CI/CD** | GitHub Actions: lint + unit + integration tests + Vite build on every push |
| **7-Page Dashboard** | Executive Overview, Forecast Lab, Inventory Risk, Product Drilldown, Model Quality, Scenario Lab, About |

---

## Tech Stack

| Layer | Technology |
|-------|-----------|
| Language | Python 3.11+ |
| Data Processing | Polars (primary), Pandas (LightGBM compat) |
| Data Quality | Pandera |
| Warehouse | PostgreSQL 16 + dbt-core 1.7+ |
| ML | LightGBM 4.x, statsforecast |
| Uncertainty | LightGBM quantile + conformal prediction |
| Reconciliation | hierarchicalforecast (Nixtla) |
| Experiment Tracking | MLflow 2.x |
| Simulation | NumPy / SciPy (Monte Carlo) |
| Frontend | Vite + React 18 + TypeScript + Tailwind CSS |
| Charts | ECharts 5.x |
| Deployment | Hugging Face Static Space |
| CI/CD | GitHub Actions |
| Testing | pytest (795 tests) |

